# Intentionally empty.
#
# Firebase Hosting requires a `public` directory, but this app must NOT serve
# its files from Hosting's CDN. Hosting serves whatever is in `public` BEFORE
# consulting rewrites, so any file placed here is world-readable with no token
# check.
#
# The paid roadmap under protected/ is gated by server.js, which checks a signed
# access token on GET /api/content/:name and blocks sensitive paths from the
# static handler. A blanket upload of the repo to Hosting would hand out
# protected/data.js and protected/app.jsx to anyone who asked — the paywall
# would be gone, which is the exact thing DEPLOY.md says this architecture
# exists to prevent.
#
# So this directory stays empty and firebase.json rewrites ** to Cloud Run,
# letting the Express server keep ownership of every route. The cost is that
# static assets are served by Cloud Run rather than the CDN (slower, and they
# bill as requests). If that ever matters, the fix is to serve ONLY the known
# public assets from here (styles.css, boot.jsx, the legal pages) — never a
# blanket upload of the repo.
